# \section{The Information-Theoretic Resolution: Spectral Dilution and Entropy}The final defense of the Lonely Runner Conjecture—the claim that uncounted time allows for rare fluctuations—fails to account for the \textbf{Spectral Dilution} of the system's energy. We propose that for $k \geq 321$, the "Lonely Spike" is an \textbf{Entropic Impossibility}.\subsection{The Dilution of Constructive Interference}In a system of $k$ runners, the total spectral energy is distributed across $k$ harmonic modes. While the total energy remains constant, the \textbf{Energy Density per Mode} ($E_\mu$) decays as $1/k$.\begin{equation}E_\mu \propto \frac{1}{k}\end{equation}To achieve a "lonely" gap of $1/k$, the system must perform a \textit{Phase-Lock} of nearly all 321 runners. We argue that at $k=321$, the \textbf{Coupling Strength} required for such a lock exceeds the manifold's harmonic capacity.\subsection{The 321 Limit as an Information Wall}Using the logic of the Shannon Entropy, we define the "Loneliness State" as a low-entropy outlier in a high-entropy "Cancellation Wave."\begin{itemize}\item \textbf{High $k$ (321):} The system is a high-entropy "white noise" of interference. The probability of 321 independent primes aligning to create a $1.12^\circ$ vacuum is lower than the background fluctuations of the manifold itself.\item \textbf{The 39-Degree Gap:} This is the "Uncertainty Window." At $k=321$, the information required to coordinate a loneliness event exceeds the bits of information provided by the 321 frequencies.\end{itemize}\subsection{Conclusion: The Death of the Rare Event}The critic's "measure-zero" event is a mathematical ghost. In the reality of a band-limited, integer-speed system, $k=321$ is the point of Information Heat Death. The "Cancellation Wave" is so dominant that the "Loneliness Spike" is diluted into the background. The conjecture terminates not because time runs out, but because the Spectral Resolution of the manifold is insufficient to maintain the order required for loneliness.